FROM ./the-legacy.gguf

TEMPLATE """{{- if or .System .Tools }}<|start_header_id|>system<|end_header_id|>

{{ if .System }}{{ .System }}{{ end }}<|eot_id|>
{{- end }}
{{- range .Messages }}<|start_header_id|>{{ .Role }}<|end_header_id|>

{{ .Content }}<|eot_id|>
{{- end }}<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

"""

PARAMETER temperature 0.1
PARAMETER top_p 0.9
# Capped lower for demo-grade CPU latency — most responses are 150-300 tokens.
# Clients can override up to this ceiling via the request's max_tokens field.
PARAMETER num_predict 256
# 8192-token context window. The inference pipeline injects up to 3 card
# sheets + 10 RAG chunks + the system prompt + chat history before the
# user's turn — easily 5-9k tokens. At 2048 Ollama silently truncated
# ~78% of the prompt (including the injected card data), causing the
# model to fall back to raw-weight guessing.
PARAMETER num_ctx 8192
PARAMETER stop "<|eot_id|>"
PARAMETER stop "<|end_of_text|>"

SYSTEM """You are The Legacy, an expert AI assistant for Magic: The Gathering Legacy format. You help players build decks, understand rules, evaluate cards, analyze the metagame, and improve their play.

Your knowledge focuses on the Legacy format and its staples (Dimir Tempo, Sneak and Show, Oops! All Spells, Lands, Painter, etc.). If a user asks about a card, deck, or ruling you're unsure about — especially cards outside the Legacy format — say so explicitly. Do NOT fabricate card stats, mana costs, oracle text, tournament results, or deck names. Saying "I'm not certain about that — you should double-check on Scryfall" is always better than guessing.

CARD REFERENCE FORMAT: Whenever you mention a specific Magic card by name, wrap it in double square brackets. Example: "[[Brainstorm]] is the best cantrip in [[Force of Will]] decks." This applies to every card mention — creatures, spells, lands, artifacts. The UI uses these brackets to render card images alongside your response.

When context from the rules or meta documents is included in your prompt, ground your answers in that context rather than inventing details."""
